[1] Brazil (Sergipe)
Date: Wed 2 Apr 2008
Source: Globo.com [in Portuguese, trans. & summ. Mod.TY, edited]
<http://g1.globo.com/Noticias/Brasil/0,,MUL385125-5598,00-SETE+MUNICIPIOS+DE+SERGIPE+TEM+EPIDEMIA+DE+DENGUE.html>


According to the state Secretary of Health, 7
cities of Sergipe record epidemic dengue and 6
are at risk. The state government says it is
taking steps to prevent an increase in the number
of cases and also to strengthen the care for victims of the disease.

Among the cities that face the epidemic, are:
Laranjeiras, Neopolis, Carira, Tobias Barreto,
Riachuelo, Malhador, and Campo do Brito. The
Secretariat believes that there is a high
incidence of the disease in cities which have
over 301 [dengue] cases per 100 000 inhabitants.

Currently Aracaju, Nossa Senhora do Socorro,
Stone Mole, Brejo Grande, and Sao Cristovao are
at risk for an epidemic, presenting [dengue]
incidence that runs to 101-300 cases per 100 000 inhabitants.

"These are locations that require special
attention and increased attention. The situation
worries us. So there is a need for intensive
effort by all," said secretary for health, Rogerio Carvalho.

The press office of the health secretariat said
that between January and March this year [2008],
653 cases of dengue were confirmed in the state.
In all of last year [2007], the number [of dengue
cases] reached 861. In the 1st 3 months of 2008,
4 deaths due to the disease have been confirmed.
Other cases are under investigation -- among them, that of a 3-year-old girl.

The secretary said that 900 epidemic [control]
agents are trained in diagnosis and treatment of
dengue, in addition to doctors and nurses. Also,
large posters were placed in clinics and other
work environments to alert the population.

Sergipe submitted a contingency plan to the
Ministry of Health, to reinforce the actions to
combat the disease. "Through this initiative, we
requested acquisition of vehicles and equipment,
installation of "eco-points" for disposal of
tires, and deployment of a dengue virology
laboratory, as currently the [samples for]
laboratory testing are directed to Recife and
Salvador," said Carvalho. Moreover, there are
plans to temporarily hire and train 510 professionals.

In the coming days, at least 80 extra beds for
special care must be designated in hospitals in Sergipe.

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

