[2] Brazil (Rio de Janeiro)
Date: Wed 2 Apr 2008
Source: O Globo Online [in Portuguese, trans. & summ. Mod.TY, edited]
<http://oglobo.globo.com/pais/mat/2008/04/02/menina_de_tres_anos_morre_com_dengue_hemorragica_em_sergipe-426646316.asp>


In Rio de Janeiro, the epidemic of dengue
collapsed the public health network this Tuesday
[1 Apr 2008]. All 607 vacancies in federal,
state, and municipal hospitals reserved by the
central [office] for regulation of [hospital]
beds for the victims of the dengue [virus
transmitting] mosquito were occupied. There were
also no beds available in the 9 private
hospitals, including those outside the
municipality, that have been contracted by the state government.

On Monday [31 Mar 2008], the municipal Department
of Health confirmed 13 more deaths from dengue in
Rio, 5 of them children. With these, the number
of dengue deaths reaches at least 67 in the state
since January [2008], 40 of them children.

This Monday [31 Mar 2008], a report from the
Ministry of Health disclosed that the incidence
of dengue in Brazil fell 27 percent in the 1st 2
months of 2008. Currently [at the national
level], as of [the 13th week of the year (23-29
March [2008]), a total of 120 570 dengue cases
have been reported in the country.

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-PORT
<promed@promedmail.org>

[An additional ProMED-PORT report published in
Portuguese in Estadao on 31 Mar 2008
(http:www.estadao.com.br) indicated that Rio
[city] had 44 dengue deaths, 23 of whom were
children up to 12 years of age. There have been
67 dengue deaths in the state. In the entire
country, there have been 74 dengue-related deaths
-- 48 from DHF and the remainder from
complications caused by the infection. ProMED
Rapporteur A-Lan Banks is thanked for sending in a similar report. - Mod.TY]

******
[3] Guadeloupe
Date: Tue 25 Mar 2008
Source: Institut de Veille Sanitaire, Point
Epidemiologique [in French, trans. & summ. Mod.TY, edited]
<http://www.invs.sante.fr/presse/2008/le_point_sur/dengue_pep_guadeloupe_270308/PEP_Guadeloupe_2008_03_dengue.pdf>


[This article presents a summary of the 2007
dengue epidemic in Guadeloupe as follows:]

Epidemic figures:
- number of clinical cases estimated during the course of the epidemic: 19 200
- duration of the epidemic: 17 weeks (from [calendar] week 35 to week 52, 2007]
- epidemic peak: week 43 (end October 2007)
- number of hospitalizations during the epidemic:
272 (46 percent children less than 15 years of age)
- rate of severe cases: 0.8 percent (among adults
hospitalized, 60 percent had a severe form of the
disease, 5 percent had DHF or dengue shock
syndrome [DSS], 25 percent had incomplete
hemorrhagic disease, and 30 percent other severe
forms. Among the hospitalized children, 53
percent had a severe form of the disease: 10
percent DHF or DSS, 9 percent incomplete
hemorrhagic disease, and 33 percent other severe forms.
- predominant [dengue virus] serotype: DEN-2
(Feb-Aug 2007); DEN-1 [virus] (appeared in
September until the end of the epidemic, increasing between Sept-Dec 2007)
- number of [dengue] deaths during the epidemic:
3 including 2 directly linked to DEN-2 [virus infection]

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[It is not clear what is meant by "incomplete
hemorrhagic disease"; perhaps these are milder
DHF cases or classical dengue fever with some
hemorrhagic manifestations. This report does not
indicate if the dengue epidemic continued into
2008. ProMED-mail would appreciate any additional
information that might be available about 2008.

A map showing the location of Guadeloupe in the Caribbean can be accessed at
<http://www.worldatlas.com/webimage/countrys/namerica/caribb/gp.htm>. - Mod.TY]

******
[4] New Zealand ex Tonga
Date: Wed 2 Apr 2008
Source: New Zealand Herald [edited]
<http://www.nzherald.co.nz/section/2/story.cfm?c_id=2&objectid=10501648>


So far at least 23 New Zealanders have contracted
the viral disease [dengue], which is spread
through infected mosquitoes. Auckland medical
officer of health Dr Simon Baker said 2 of the
people have had to be hospitalised.

"It's an ongoing outbreak in Tonga and people
need to be cautious there," Dr Baker said.

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail Rapporteur A-Lan Banks

[ProMED-mail reported over 200 dengue cases in
Tonga as of 2 Mar 2008 (see archive no.
20080309.0962). One would infer from the report
above of dengue cases showing up in New Zealand
that the epidemic in Tonga continues. ProMED
would appreciate further information from Tonga
concerning the dengue outbreak there.

A map of the Tonga islands and their location in
the South Pacific can be accessed at
<http://www.infoplease.com/atlas/country/tonga.html>. - Mod.TY]

******
[5] Philippines (Negros Oriental)
Date: Wed 2 Apr 2008
Source: Sun Star [edited]
<http://www.sunstar.com.ph/static/dum/2008/04/02/news/dengue.cases.in.negros.oriental.down.by.50..html>


According to the Department of Health (DOH),
cases of dengue in Negros Oriental have decreased
by 50 percent this March [2008]. The Epidemiology
Surveillance Unit of the DOH shows that there
were only 34 cases of dengue from 1-26 Mar this
year [2008] compared to 70 cases in February.

The survey also showed that the 70 cases of
dengue in February [2008] are lower by 45 percent
compared to [the 130] cases recorded in January.

According to Dr Socrates Villamor, chief of
epidemiology, the decrease of dengue cases in
February and March [2008] is due to the summer
season. However, he reminded the public not to
get [comfortable with] the result of the survey
because dengue cases this year are still high as compared to last 2007.

There were 234 cases from January to 26 Mar this
year [2008] compared to 134 [during the same]
period last year [2007]. Dengue case [numbers]
are higher by 100 victims compared to last year [2007], he said.

With this development, Dr Villamor advised local
residents to continue the 4 o'clock habit to
clean their surroundings to avoid dengue
infections [by eliminating breeding sites for the
_Aedes_ dengue virus vector mosquito. - Mod.TY].

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail Rapporteur A-Lan Banks

[The reduction in dengue cases is good news.
However, one hopes that health providers and
local citizens will heed Dr Villamor's advice and
continue eliminating mosquito breeding sites in
and around their houses and other buildings so
that the dengue incidence will not increase when the rains return.

A map of Philippine provinces, showing Negros Oriental can be accessed at
<http://www.reliefweb.int/mapc/asi_se/cnt/phil/phl_ad.html>. - Mod.TY]
